2.) Carefully explain the differences between the KNN classifier and KNN regression methods.

2.) Answer KNN classifier assigns classification group based on majority of closest observations while the KNN regression averages the closest observations to an estimated prediction.

  1. This question should be answered using the Carseats data set.

10a.) Fit a multiple regression model to predict Sales using Price, Urban, and US.

                data(Carseats)

                fit.lm <- lm(Sales ~ Price + Urban + US, data=Carseats)

                summary(fit.lm)

10b.) Provide an interpretation of each coefficient in the model. Be carefulsome of the variables in the model are qualitative!

Sales: sales in thousands at each location Price: price charged for car seats at each location Urban: No/Yes by location US: No/Yes by location

Coefficients for

Price (-0.054459): Sales drop by 54 for each dollar increase in Price and statistically significant UrbanYes (-0.021916): Sales are 22 lower for Urban locations and not statistically significant USYes (1.200573): Sales are 1,201 higher in the US locations and statistically significant

10c.) Write out the model in equation form, being careful to handle the qualitative variables properly.

10c.) Answer: Sales = 13.043 - 0.054 x Price - 0.022 x UrbanYes + 1.201 x USYes

10d.) For which of the predictors can you reject the null hypothesis H0 : j = 0?

10d.) Answer: Can reject null hypothesis for Price and USYes (coefficients have low p-values)

10e.) On the basis of your response to the previous question, fit a smaller model that only uses the predictors for which there is evidence of association with the outcome.

12.This problem involves simple linear regression without an intercept.

12a.) Recall that the coefficient estimate (-hat) for the linear regression of Y onto X without an intercept is given by (3.38). Under what circumstance is the coefficient estimate for the regression of X onto Y the same as the coefficient estimate for the regression of Y onto X?

12a.) Answer: When \(x_{i}=y_{i}\) , or more generally when the beta denominators are equal \(\sum x_{i}^2=\sum y_{i}^2\)

12b.) Generate an example in R with n = 100 observations in which the coefficient estimate for the regression of X onto Y is different from the coefficient estimate for the regression of Y onto X.

                set.seed(1)
                x <- rnorm(100)
                y <- 2*x + rnorm(100)

                fit.lmY <- lm(y ~ x)
                fit.lmX <- lm(x ~ y)

                summary(fit.lmY)
